	<p>Warren Buffett, Elon Musk and Larry Ellison have all accumulated huge followings on Twitter, but they had to start somewhere.</p><p>All these men have large net worths and personalities, but here's how they introduced themselves to a world capped at 140 characters (oh, and happy #socialmediaday). </p><h2></h2><p>Probably one of the most famous tweets is also the first tweet ever. The CEO and co-founder of Twitter tweeted out in March of 2006:</p><blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en"><p>just setting up my twttr</p>— Jack (@jack) <a>March 21, 2006</a></blockquote><script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script><p>And no, he’s not just saving characters: at that point the company was called twttr.</p><h2></h2><p>Buffett is known for punchy catchphrases such as, “Buy businesses that can be run by idiots,” and, "The difference between successful people and really successful people is that really successful people say no to almost everything."</p><p>So it’s no surprise that Buffett’s first tweet comes as a short punchline. </p><blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en"><p>Warren is in the house.</p>— Warren Buffett (@WarrenBuffett) <a>May 2, 2013</a></blockquote><script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script><p>Just a few retweets. No big deal.</p><h2></h2><p>There are plenty of fake Elon Musk accounts on Twitter, some of the funniest being <a>@BoredElonMusk</a> and <a>@therichwiseman</a>, but Musk made sure to let followers know his first tweet was legitimate:</p><blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en"><p>Please ignore prior tweets, as that was someone pretending to be me :) This is actually me.</p>— Elon Musk (@elonmusk) <a>June 4, 2010</a></blockquote><script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script><p>He even used a smiley face. How nice.</p><h2></h2><p>Omidyar’s first tweet reads:</p><blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en"><p>wondering what all the fuss is about</p>— Pierre Omidyar (@pierre) <a>February 3, 2007</a></blockquote><script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script><p>Apparently the “fuss” was worth it to the eBay founder, because he has to date tweeted more than 7,000 times.</p><p>Omidyar takes to Twitter to frequently comment on politics -- or, to be specific, Donald Trump.</p><h2></h2><p>Sure, it took Icahn a little while to get on board with Twitter, but he does pretty well when it comes to social media for an 80 year old.</p><p>The investor has accumulated almost 300,000 followers since his first tweet in 2013, mostly tweeting about his business endeavors.</p><p>Icahn resorted to humor for his first tweet:</p><blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en"><p>Twitter is great. I like it almost as much as I like Dell.</p>— Carl Icahn (@Carl_C_Icahn) <a>June 20, 2013</a></blockquote><script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script><h2></h2><p>As the first president of Facebook, Parker was likely hesitant to get on board with a competitor.</p><p>However, he reluctantly joined in 2011.</p><p>In his first tweet, Parker apologizes to Mark Zuckerberg, claiming that Scooter Braun, talent manager and owner of two record labels, made him do it.</p><blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en"><p>Sorry Zuck, I had to do it eventually. (Actually <a>@scooterbraun</a> made me do it.)</p>— Sean Parker (@sparker) <a>October 3, 2011</a></blockquote><script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script><h2></h2><p>Like any (then) 80-year-old, Murdoch’s first tweet was a little bit of a struggle.</p><blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en"><p>Have just. Read The Rational Optimist. Great book.</p>— Rupert Murdoch (@rupertmurdoch) <a>December 31, 2011</a></blockquote><script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script><p>But he has improved since, often making headlines with his tweets.</p><p>Murdoch tweeted in March of 2016, the day of his wedding, that he was leaving Twitter.</p><h2></h2><p>Ellison’s first tweet was also his last, but he still has more than 90,000 followers.</p><p>Of course, Ellison had to take the opportunity to comment on his competitors and highlight <a>Oracle Cloud Services</a>. His one tweet wouldn’t be wasted.</p><blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en"><p>Oracle's got 100+ enterprise applications live in the <a>#cloud</a> today, SAP's got nothin' but SuccessFactors until 2020</p>— Larry Ellison (@larryellison) <a>June 6, 2012</a></blockquote><script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script><div> </div>

	
				
				
